{{Other people|John Barker}}
'''John Barker''' (fl. ca. 1471&ndash;1482) was first recorded as a King's Scholar at [[Eton College]] about 1471. He went to King's College in 1474, was elected a fellow in 1477, and graduated MA in 1479.<ref>So the ''DNB'' and ''ODNB''. The original edition of Venn distinguished two men of the same name: {{acad|id=BRKR4..J|name=Barker, John}}</ref> His Etonian connection may indicate that he was from the south of England.
Barker taught logic to "sophisters" (second-year undergraduates) using his own text, the ''[[Scutum inexpugnabile]]''. No copy survives, but it was probably an introduction to [[Aristotle|Aristotelian]] [[logic]] and [[modal grammar]]. [[Brian Rowe]], who came up to King's in 1499, wrote a commendatory preface for it in the early 16th century, indicating that it was then still in use in the college. Barker left King's in 1482, approximately the year [[John Fisher]] and [[John Colet]] came to Cambridge, and later joined the Franciscans. The date and place of his death are unknown.<ref>{{cite web|last=Leader|first=Damian R.|title=Barker, John (fl. c.1471–1482), logician|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/1401?docPos=1|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=31 July 2011}}</ref>
